.TH VULNSCAN-AI 1 "July 2026" "vulnscan-ai @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
vulnscan-ai \- RHEL vulnerability scanner with AI-assisted, approval-gated remediation
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B vulnscan-ai
[\fIGLOBAL OPTIONS\fR]
.I COMMAND
[\fICOMMAND OPTIONS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B vulnscan-ai
scans RHEL-based hosts (RHEL, AlmaLinux, Rocky, CentOS Stream, Fedora) for known
vulnerabilities using the package manager (dnf/RHSA), OpenSCAP/OVAL, and public
CVE feeds (Red Hat Security Data API, NIST NVD). It then uses a large language
model (Claude by default; OpenAI, Gemini, Kimi, or a local Ollama model
optionally) to propose remediation. Fixes are applied only after explicit
approval and only after passing a safety deny-list.
.PP
The tool is FIPS-aware: it relies on the system OpenSSL, pins TLS 1.2+, and uses
SHA-2 digests only. It can export PDF, HTML, JSON, and SARIF 2.1.0 reports, and
ships a systemd timer for unattended scan-and-report.
.SH GLOBAL OPTIONS
These precede the command.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the version and exit.
.TP
.BI \-\-config " CONFIG"
Path to a configuration JSON file.
.TP
.BI \-\-state\-dir " DIR"
Override the state/cache directory (findings and reports).
.TP
.BI \-\-provider " PROVIDER"
AI provider: \fBclaude\fR, \fBopenai\fR, \fBgemini\fR, \fBkimi\fR, \fBdeepseek\fR, \fBmistral\fR, or \fBlocal\fR.
.TP
.BI \-\-model " MODEL"
Model id override, e.g. \fIclaude-opus-4-8\fR or \fIllama3.2:1b\fR.
.TP
.BI \-\-effort " LEVEL"
Claude reasoning effort: \fBlow\fR, \fBmedium\fR, \fBhigh\fR, \fBxhigh\fR, or \fBmax\fR. Turns on adaptive thinking; other providers ignore it.
.TP
.BI \-\-no\-banner
Suppress the startup banner.
.SH SEVERITY VALUES
Where a severity is accepted, use one of, in increasing order:
.BR low ", " moderate ", " important ", " critical
(\fBhigh\fR is treated as \fBimportant\fR, \fBmedium\fR as \fBmoderate\fR).
.SH COMMANDS
.SS menu
Launch an interactive, menu-driven front-end that covers every command, so flags
need not be memorised. Running
.B vulnscan-ai
with no command on a terminal opens the same menu. Navigate with the arrow keys
and Enter (press \fBq\fR or Esc to go back); on terminals without cursor support
(or with \fBVULNSCANAI_NO_CURSES=1\fR) it falls back to a numbered prompt. Piped,
non-interactive invocations print help instead. No options.
.SS info
Show version, FIPS status, GPU/CPU, available scanners, and AI provider readiness.
No options.
.SS scan
Detect vulnerabilities, enrich from CVE feeds, print a table, and save findings.
.TP
.BI \-\-scanner " NAME"
Scanner to run (repeatable): \fBdnf\fR, \fBoscap\fR, \fBssh\fR, \fBsystemd\fR, \fBports\fR, \fBwebroot\fR, \fBcontainer\fR, \fBeffective\fR (reboot/restart still pending after a patch), or \fBfips\fR (FIPS-mode & crypto-policy posture). Use \fB\-\-all\fR to run every available scanner.
.TP
.BI \-\-min\-severity " SEV"
Only keep findings at or above this severity.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-enrich
Skip Red Hat/NVD CVE-feed lookups (faster; fully offline).
.TP
.BI \-\-pdf " PATH"
Also write a PDF report.
.TP
.BI \-\-json " PATH"
Also write a JSON export.
.TP
.BI \-\-sarif " PATH"
Also write a SARIF 2.1.0 file.
.TP
.BI \-\-compliance " PROFILE"
Run a compliance benchmark (CIS, DISA STIG, PCI-DSS, HIPAA, ...) instead of a
vulnerability scan, via \fBoscap xccdf eval\fR against the SCAP Security Guide.
Reports a compliance score and every failing rule (sorted by severity, with
CCE/CIS/STIG identifiers and whether an automated fix ships), saves them to
\fI<state-dir>/compliance.json\fR, and honours \fB\-\-pdf\fR/\fB\-\-json\fR/\fB\-\-sarif\fR.
Exits \fB3\fR when any rule fails. Not part of \fB\-\-all\fR. \fIPROFILE\fR is an
alias (\fBcis-l1\fR, \fBcis-l2\fR, \fBstig\fR, \fBpci-dss\fR, \fBhipaa\fR, ...) or a
full XCCDF profile id; omit it to use the configured \fBcompliance_profile\fR.
Requires the \fBscap-security-guide\fR package.
.TP
.B \-\-list\-profiles
List the compliance profiles this host's SCAP datastream offers, then exit.
.TP
.BI \-\-compliance\-datastream " PATH"
Override the SCAP datastream (default: auto-detect for this distro).
.SS fix
Propose remediation, then apply with approval. Proposed commands are screened
against a safety deny-list. Package/advisory findings (\fBdnf\fR/\fBoscap\fR) are
planned by a deterministic offline catalog (a scoped \fBdnf update
\-\-advisory=<id>\fR) with no AI call, so \fBfix\fR works air-gapped; the AI
provider is used only for config/service findings that need reasoning. The
per-finding prompt accepts \fBy\fR (yes), \fBn\fR (no), \fBi\fR (ignore), \fBa\fR
(all), or \fBq\fR (quit). \fBi\fR writes the finding to the persistent baseline
(\fI~/.config/vulnscan-ai/ignore\fR) so future scans suppress it. During apply
each step is streamed live (backup, every command, validate, service
reload/health check, and rollback) together with the command's output.
.TP
.B \-\-scan
Scan first instead of using the last saved findings.
.TP
.BI \-\-scanner " NAME"
Scanner(s) to use with \fB\-\-scan\fR (repeatable).
.TP
.B \-\-no\-enrich
Skip CVE-feed enrichment with \fB\-\-scan\fR.
.TP
.BI \-\-min\-severity " SEV"
Only act on findings at or above this severity.
.TP
.B \-\-yes
Auto-approve every screened fix (non-interactive).
.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Produce the plan but execute nothing.
.TP
.BI \-\-pdf " PATH"
Write a PDF report after fixing.
.TP
.B \-\-offline
Plan fixes from the deterministic offline catalog only; never call an AI provider
(air-gapped). Mutually exclusive with \fB\-\-no\-catalog\fR.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-catalog
Disable the offline catalog; use the AI provider for every finding.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-scap\-grounding
Disable grounding AI prompts with matching SCAP Security Guide hardening-rule
snippets (see \fBscap_grounding\fR in the config file). No effect when
\fBscap-security-guide\fR isn't installed.
.SS audit
Show the append\-only remediation audit log. Every fix actually applied (or
rolled back), from the CLI or the web dashboard, is recorded as one JSON line in
\fI<state-dir>/audit.log\fR (mode 0600) with a UTC timestamp, source
(cli/dashboard), actor, result and the commands run. Dry\-run previews are not
recorded. The log is independent of \fBfindings.json\fR and survives re\-scans.
.TP
.BI \-\-limit " N"
Show the most recent \fBN\fR events (default 50; \fB0\fR = all).
.TP
.B \-\-json
Emit the raw events as JSON.
.SS report
Render a report or export from the last saved scan. The output extension selects
the format: \fI.pdf\fR, \fI.html\fR, \fI.json\fR, or \fI.sarif\fR.
.TP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-output " " \fIPATH\fR
Output file (default \fIvulnscan-ai-report.pdf\fR).
.TP
.BI \-\-min\-severity " SEV"
Only include findings at or above this severity.
.SS providers
List AI providers, default models, key environment variables, and readiness.
No options.
.SS setup
Interactive first-run wizard: detect GPU/RAM, list offline models sized to the
host, optionally install Ollama, download the chosen model, and save it as the
default provider/model. Offered automatically on the first interactive run;
suppress with \fBVULNSCANAI_NO_SETUP=1\fR. No options.
.SS update\-oval
Detect the distribution and download/stage the OpenSCAP OVAL CVE feed under
\fI<state-dir>/oval/\fR, enabling the \fBoscap\fR scanner. No options. You rarely
need this by hand: a scan that uses \fBoscap\fR auto-refreshes the feed when it is
missing or older than \fBoval_max_age_days\fR (default 7), unless offline
(\fB\-\-no\-enrich\fR) or \fBoval_auto_update\fR is false.
.SS scheduled
Non-interactive scan and dated report for the systemd timer or cron. Never
applies fixes. Rotates old reports and can signal severity via the exit code.
.TP
.BI \-\-scanner " NAME"
Scanner(s) to run (repeatable).
.TP
.B \-\-no\-enrich
Skip CVE-feed enrichment.
.TP
.BI \-\-min\-severity " SEV"
Only keep findings at or above this severity.
.TP
.B \-\-plan
Embed AI remediation proposals in the report (no execution).
.TP
.B \-\-html
Write an HTML report instead of PDF.
.TP
.BI \-\-keep " N"
Retain only the newest N reports (default 30).
.TP
.BI \-\-fail\-on " SEVERITY"
Exit 3 if any finding is at or above this severity.
.SS dashboard
Serve the saved findings over a local HTTPS login dashboard (stdlib only,
self-signed certificate). Includes an \fBAdvisories\fR tab with recent
vulnerability news. Localhost-only unless an allow-list is configured.
.TP
.B \-\-set\-password
Prompt for and store the admin password, then exit.
.TP
.BI \-\-user " NAME"
Admin username (default \fBadmin\fR).
.TP
.BI \-\-port " PORT"
Listen port (default 65101).
.TP
.BI \-\-allow ", " \-\-deny " IP/CIDR"
Permit / remove a network client (besides loopback).
.TP
.B \-\-list
Show dashboard settings (including the apply-fix state), then exit.
.TP
.B \-\-enable\-fix
Allow applying fixes from the dashboard UI (sets \fBdashboard_allow_fix=true\fR),
then exit. This grants anyone who can log into the dashboard root\-equivalent
remediation power \(em keep the password strong and the allow\-list tight.
.TP
.B \-\-disable\-fix
Disable applying fixes from the dashboard UI (preview only), then exit.
.SS news
Show recent vulnerability advisories aggregated from public feeds: CISA KEV
(actively exploited), NIST NVD (recent CVEs) and the host distribution's errata.
Locally-relevant advisories (matching the last scan) are flagged. The same feeds
flag scan findings that are actively exploited (CISA KEV) and carry an EPSS
exploit-probability score.
.TP
.BI \-\-source " NAME"
Show only one feed source: \fBkev\fR, \fBnvd\fR, or \fBdistro\fR.
.TP
.B \-\-refresh
Fetch fresh data instead of using the on-disk cache.
.TP
.BI \-\-limit " N"
Maximum advisories to show (default 30).
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
No findings to act on, or a step failed (e.g. OVAL download).
.TP
.B 2
AI provider error (key missing, or model/server unreachable).
.TP
.B 3
\fBscheduled \-\-fail\-on\fR threshold met.
.TP
.B 130
Interrupted.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
API key for the \fBclaude\fR provider (default).
.TP
.BR OPENAI_API_KEY ", " GEMINI_API_KEY ", " MOONSHOT_API_KEY
API keys for \fBopenai\fR, \fBgemini\fR, and \fBkimi\fR respectively.
.TP
.BR OLLAMA_HOST ", " OLLAMA_MODEL ", " OLLAMA_TIMEOUT
Local (\fBlocal\fR) provider: server URL, model name, request timeout (seconds).
.TP
.B NVD_API_KEY
Optional; raises the NVD enrichment rate limit.
.TP
.BR VULNSCANAI_PROVIDER ", " VULNSCANAI_MODEL ", " VULNSCANAI_STATE_DIR
Override the provider, model, and state directory.
.TP
.B VULNSCANAI_NO_SETUP
If set, never run the first-run wizard automatically.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/vulnscan-ai/config.json
System configuration.
.TP
.I ~/.config/vulnscan-ai/config.json
Per-user configuration (where the setup wizard saves its choice).
.TP
.I /var/lib/vulnscan-ai/
State directory: findings.json, audit.log, reports/, oval/.
.SH "CONFIGURATION PRECEDENCE"
Highest wins: command-line flags, then environment variables, then the per-user
config, then the system config, then built-in defaults.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR dnf (8),
.BR oscap (8),
.BR systemctl (1).
Full reference and examples: \fI/usr/share/doc/vulnscan-ai/COMMANDS.md\fR.
